      <h2>Understanding Golden Visa Document Requirements</h2>
      <div class="content-prose">
        <p>The UAE Golden Visa has transformed residency for professionals, investors, and talented individuals. Unlike standard employment visas tied to specific sponsors, the Golden Visa offers 5 or 10 years of residency with significant flexibility. However, the application process requires careful documentation, and translation plays a critical role in how ICP evaluates your application.</p>
        
        <p>Each Golden Visa category has specific document requirements. Skilled employees must demonstrate both qualification (through degree equivalency) and income level (through salary documentation). Investors must prove asset ownership and value. Specialized talents must evidence their achievements and recognition. Understanding exactly what each category requires helps you prepare a complete and compelling application.</p>
        
        <h3>Why Translation Quality Matters for Golden Visa</h3>
        <p>ICP reviewers assess your application based on the Arabic translations of your documents. If the translation of your salary certificate omits key details or uses non-standard terminology, your application may be queried or rejected—even if the original document contained all required information.</p>
        
        <p>We have seen applications delayed because salary certificates lacked the phrase confirming permanent employment, or because degree certificates were translated without including the specialization details that MOHESR requires for equivalency. These are not translation errors in the traditional sense—the English was correctly rendered—but failures to include what the receiving authorities specifically need to see.</p>
        
        <p>Our approach addresses this by understanding what ICP and MOHESR actually look for, then ensuring translations include those elements prominently. When your HR department provides a salary letter, we know which elements must be present and can advise if anything is missing before we translate.</p>
        
        <h3>The Degree Equivalency Process</h3>
        <p>For most Golden Visa applicants, degree equivalency through MOHESR is a critical step. This process verifies that your foreign degree is equivalent to a UAE qualification, which ICP requires for the skilled employee category.</p>
        
        <p>MOHESR evaluates your degree based on the institution, the programme of study, and the qualification level. Translations must accurately convey these details. The degree title, specialization, and any honors or distinctions all matter for the equivalency assessment.</p>
        
        <p>Some applicants also need to submit academic transcripts, particularly when the degree title alone does not clearly indicate the field of study. We translate transcripts with the course titles and grades preserved accurately, allowing MOHESR to assess the substance of your education.</p>
        
        <h3>Salary Documentation Requirements</h3>
        <p>The salary certificate is arguably the most important document for the skilled employee category. ICP has specific expectations about what this document should contain and how it should be phrased.</p>
        
        <p>Required elements include: your full name, job title, date of joining, current monthly salary in AED, and a statement that your employment is permanent or of ongoing nature. The salary must meet the minimum threshold for your visa category. The letter should be on company letterhead, signed by an authorized signatory, and dated recently.</p>
        
        <p>We translate salary certificates using the exact Arabic terminology that ICP expects. This is not a matter of word choice—it is using the specific phrases that reviewers look for when processing applications. Years of handling these documents have taught us what works.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

